  <h2>Choosing the Right Location</h2>

  <p>
    Where you place the litter box matters deeply to your cat. They seek privacy
    for this vulnerable moment, but not isolation. Quiet accessibility is the goal.
  </p>

  <p>
    Avoid high-traffic areas where your cat might feel interrupted. Equally, avoid
    forgotten corners where they might feel trapped or anxious. The ideal location
    offers a clear view of the surroundingsâ€”cats want to see if anyone approaches
    while they're occupied.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider your cat's age and mobility. Senior cats or those with joint issues
    benefit from easily accessible locations, not hidden basement corners requiring
    stairs. The path to the litter box should be clear and comfortable.
  </p>

  <h2>The Container Itself</h2>

  <p>
    Litter boxes come in endless varieties, but simplicity often serves best.
    Covered boxes feel private to humans but can trap odors and make cats feel
    cornered. Open boxes with high sides often strike the right balance.
  </p>

  <p>
    Size matters more than features. Your cat should be able to turn around
    completely, dig comfortably, and position themselves without crowding. When
    in doubt, go larger.
  </p>

  <p>
    The material should be easy to clean. Smooth plastic that can be wiped down
    and occasionally washed keeps the space hygienic without harsh scrubbing.
  </p>

